Wherefore on the Lord's Day following, in the middle ol the night, the whole Commonalty ol Oxsord‚ the Mayor and Baillives, accompanied by a multitude of scholars, proceeded to Abingdon with arms and hurning torches, destroying on their way the manor os Northcote. Entering the town with 'dismal shouts, to the terror os the neighbourhood, they went to the Abbey gate, insultingly cried aloud, gave base and aggravating language, threw stenes, shot arrows, and put fire to the gates. Another party went to the gate of St. John's Hospital, hoping to gain an, entrance, but those that were within, stoutly resisted them till the rising of the sun. Soon after, they went to the church of St. Nicholas, and through it entered the Abbey; Edmund de la Beche, the leader of the rabble, dragged the monks from the High Altar, and cut off the head and arm of one ol the senior ol them. In the meanwhile the Abbot and the rest ol the monks ventured to cross the river behind the Abbey, and, with the exception ol some who were drowned, made good their escape.’
